== Budget and broadcast ==

The series is one of the most elaborate docudrama formats ever co-produced in Germany and was already sold in more than 25 countries worldwide before broadcast. The budget for the German version alone was around 6 million euros,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/medien/weltkriegs-dokumentation-von-der-leichenbahre-in-die-psychiatrie-12218155.html|title=Von der Leichenbahre in die Psychiatrie|publisher=FAZ|accessdate=18 March 2014}}</ref> for all the international versions together the budget was closer to 8 million euros.

On the occasion of the 100th anniversary of the start of World War the television broadcaster, ARTE, will broadcast an eight-part series beginning on 29 April 2014 in parallel in Germany and France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arte.tv/sites/de/seiten/arte-und-der-erste-weltkrieg/|title=14 – Tagebücher des Ersten Weltkriegs bei ARTE|accessdate=18 March 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701220527/http://www.arte.tv/sites/de/seiten/arte-und-der-erste-weltkrieg/|archivedate=1 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In Germany, Partners of the series are, next to ARTE - SWR, NDR and WDR, ORF in Austria and the BBC in the UK. The ARD / ORF will broadcast the series in four episodes of 45 minutes each. The BBC will show "14 - Diaries of the First World War" under the title "Great War Diary" in three episodes of 60 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.centenarynews.com/article?id=1169|title=14 - Diaries of the Great War at the BBC|accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>

Dutch broadcasters [[Omroep NTR|NTR]] and [[VPRO]] produced an additional episode about the situation in the Netherlands which aired on 5 April 2014, on [[Nederland 2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pers.ntr.nl/programmaPopup.php?id=11549|title=Programma: 14-18 Dagboeken uit de Eerste Wereldoorlog (NTR/VPRO)|publisher=NTR/VPRO|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702020025/http://pers.ntr.nl/programmaPopup.php?id=11549|archivedate=2 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The remaining eight "international" episodes aired in the Netherlands between 12 April and 7 June.

Sweden's [[Sveriges Television|SVT]] had several additional segments produced for their airing of the series which included introductions to each episode by historian and author [[Peter Englund]] and dramatisations of diaries from six Swedes to tell the story of Sweden during the Great War.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svt.se/det-stora-kriget/livet-under-forsta-varldskriget-gestaltas-i-stor-dokumentarsatsning |title=Stor dokumentärsatsning om livet under första världskriget |publisher=SVT.se |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RL4ftaL1?url=http://www.svt.se/det-stora-kriget/livet-under-forsta-varldskriget-gestaltas-i-stor-dokumentarsatsning |archivedate=25 July 2014 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> These were edited into the original eight episodes which meant they ended up with a running time of sixty minutes. This version of the series premièred on [[SVT1]] on 26 June.

